      "content": "You are absolutely right to be skeptical; the \"unseen\" part is where the real physics gets tricky, and it's actually a debate that has been going on for nearly a century. The main theories trying to explain this \"invisible glue\" are called **Hidden Variable Theories**.\n\nEinstein, Podolsky, and Rosen (EPR) proposed that there must be some pre-existing \"hidden variables\" inside the particles—like a secret instruction manual written on the particle's DNA—that determined their outcomes all along, even before we looked. They thought the quantum world was just incomplete because it felt too random.\n\nHowever, in 1964, physicist John Bell devised a clever test (now known as **Bell's Theorem**) to see if these hidden variables could actually work. He showed that if the particles were truly communicating via hidden signals traveling at or below the speed of light, there would be specific statistical limits to how correlated they could be.\n\nWhen scientists performed these experiments starting in the 1970s and continuing today, they found that the correlations were **stronger** than any hidden variable theory could allow. This means the particles aren't just following a secret script; they are genuinely non-local,",
